Good morning, everyone. My name is Scott Bordow and I'm the new Director of Communications for the Apache Junction Unified School District.

Some background: I was a sports journalist in the Valley for 38 years, working for the Mesa Tribune, the Arizona Republic and most recently, The Athletic. I'm an Arizona State Sun Devil, as is my wife and two children.

I'm thrilled to be here and looking forward to extolling the virtues of our district and the community.

I plan on actively promoting our schools and the students on our various social media sites. I look forward to hearing from you and meeting you at different events.

Have a great day.

The Apache Junction Unified School District Governing Board is holding an in-person meeting on Thursday, August 20, 2020, in the Performing Arts Center at Apache Junction High School starting at 6 p.m. Seating is limited due to social distancing, and it is requested that all attendees wear face masks. Temperatures will be checked at the gate for all attendees.

Public Comments will be heard at the meeting or may be submitted in advance by clicking the Public Comments button on www.AJUSD.org.

Attendees who wish to speak at the meeting will be required to complete a Request to Speak form at the meeting. Those who want to submit a question or statement to the board online are encouraged to fill out the form by 4 p.m. on the day of the meeting.

AJUSD Governing Board Meeting
Thursday, August 20, 2020
6 p.m. - 8 p.m.
Performing Arts Center
Apache Junction High School
2525 S. Ironwood Drive, Apache Junction, AZ 85120

The meeting will be carried live on YouTube.

post_text:
Good evening AJUSD parents and guardians,

At last night's AJUSD Governing Board meeting, the board approved a plan for moving towards a return to in-person, teacher-led classroom instruction, if the District can do so in a manner consistent with the Pinal County Health Department/Arizona Department of Health Services public health metrics in effect at that time.

If Pinal County meets the three minimum community spread metrics*:

August 6, 2020:

New Cases - less than 100 cases out of 100,000 for two consecutive weeks
(Currently 96/100,000 - Benchmark MET)

Percent Positivity - less than 7% (Hybrid model) or less than 5% (In-person model) for two consecutive weeks
(Currently 11.1% - Benchmark NOT MET)

COVID-like Illness - less than 10% for two consecutive weeks
(Currently 8.8% - Benchmark NOT MET)

*The community spread metrics are updated every Thursday on the Arizona Department of Health Services website. https://bit.ly/3gWHYuQ

Sincerely,

Dr. Krista Anderson
Superintendent of Apache Junction Unified School District

azfamily 3TV CBS 5 reporter, Kylie Cruz and her cameraman, joined an Apache Junction Unified School District bus driver this morning as he made his rounds delivering meals to students. AJUSD Food Service prepares breakfast and lunch for students daily, and the meals are then delivered to the student's nearest school bus stop. Meals for an entire week are also being distributed at Four Peaks Elementary School and Apache Junction High School every Monday morning. At the "curbside pickup" parents and guardians pickup five-days worth of breakfast and lunch for their students at home.

To be eligible, students must be enrolled in AJUSD and register for the program.

Reminder - Receive 5 Days of Breakfast and Lunch For Your Student

AJUSD is providing curbside food pick every Monday morning at AJHS and *FPES. Parents may pick up five days worth of breakfast and lunch for the week. Meals will be available from 7:30-8:45 a.m. at both locations.

To receive free meals, you must be enrolled in an AJUSD school and qualify for free or reduced meals. Parents may also add money to their lunch accounts to receive these meals. Lunch Program Applications and prepayments can be completed online through https://family.titank12.com .

If you have questions, please contact your school. This message is for curbside pickup participants only.

*ALL FPES students receive free meals thanks to a national special assistance grant.

post_text:
Hello Apache Junction community,

As you've already heard, school opens July 21 with online instruction due to the Corona-virus global pandemic. We appreciate the support and understanding that many of you have shared. It's difficult for everyone, but we are going to shine on.

We do have a need to help our students and families. Because students are beginning their new school year at home, we will provide meals they normally would receive in school to their homes. To help us deliver the freshest food possible we are in need of additional ICE PACKS OR FROZEN GEL PACKS as well as CARDBOARD OR STYROFOAM FOOD CONTAINERS.

If you are able to help in this request, please send a note to Karen at kwarhus@goaj.org.

post_text:
We are proud to announce that Apache Junction High School and Cactus Canyon Junior High have been selected as a recipient of the 2020 Riding for Focus Grant from Outride We could not be more excited about this opportunity to get more kids on bikes and bring a cycling program to our physical education classes.

"I am proud of the work that physical education teacher Tim Mckee and the teams at AJHS and CCJH have done to earn this opportunity for our students," said AJHS Principal Christopher Lineberry. "Through programs such as this, we are meeting the needs of the whole child, promote lifelong health and physical activity, and improve the quality of life for our students. We look forward to coming back to school in person soon so that we can get our students learning and riding!"
www.outridebike.org/

#ridingforfocus
#whatwillyououtride
#morekidsonbikes
#RideBikes

post_text:
This summer AJUSD elementary students had the opportunity to experience Camp Invention online. AJUSD has been hosting Camp Invention for over 10 summers. it is a nationally recognized program that allows students to bring STEM concepts to life. Students work collaboratively with other students as teachers guide them to explore and create while problem solving to be innovative learners.

All students are encouraged to be a part of camp as it's a hands on experience that leads students into a world of creating and innovating.

Typically a week long program with approximately 200 elementary teachers and 15 staff, this year we ran the program through online meetings. Students had materials delivered directly to their homes so they had everything they needed to participate with friends and a teacher. We had 8 elementary teachers who led classes for four days in June.

Doing whatever it takes at #ajusd

post_text:
Navy JROTC Program Expands to Cactus Canyon Jr. High

CCJH is very excited to announce a new opportunity. Next year we will be piloting an 8th grade NJROTC program. This program will be in conjunction with Apache Junction High School’s nationally ranked program under the command of Lieutenant Commander Lock and Master Guns Deleonguererro. This program will give students interested in continuing in the NJROTC program a head start and potentially allow them to take more advanced courses as they progress through high school. There is NO uniform cost to join. This class will replace 1 elective per semester and is a year-long course.Anchors aweigh #ajusd

post_text:
Two options for free food.

All the info for the curbside food service is pictured below on the flyer on the left. The fresh produce program provides fresh fruits and vegetables to families each week. It is open to the entire community with no paperwork needed. Distribution will take place at Apache Junction High School, 2525 S. Ironwood Dr. in Apache Junction on Thursdays from 7:30 to 9 a.m. Participants are asked to pull in at the drive east of the football field on Southern and follow the drive around the field to the cafeteria, just under the Davis Field sign.

Both programs will continue until further notice and while supplies last. And don't forget, online registration for students is available now at www.ajusd.org. #ajusd

post_text:
The Story of Two Brothers

Every AJUSD graduate has a unique story and the Ripley Brothers are no different. Aaron (pictured in the first picture on the right) has overcome many challenges but still managed to graduate with a 4.0. He is a determined and kind lad who is always willing to lend a hand - even without being asked! He isn't letting high school be the end of his education. Aaron is going to be taking classes online at Penn Foster. He will be going to school for small engine repair. He is so excited. He even received a scholarship.

Thomas has always had an interest in cooking. Thomas was accepted to NAU and even received the dean's scholarship. Thomas has, however, decided to go to Augusta Escoffier School of Culinary Arts in Boulder, Colorado, where he has also received several scholarships from their school in addition to the local scholarship that he received.

Congratulations to these hard-working Prospectors. Well done! #ajusd

post_text:
The AJUSD Monday curbside meal program is ready to roll again. The locations include Apache Junction High School, 2525 S. Ironwood Dr. and Four Peaks Elementary School, 1785 N Idaho Road in Apache Junction. This free service is available for all children 18 years and younger.

The meal service for the AJHS site is 10 to 11:30 a.m. Participants are asked to drive up to the high school cafeteria (north parking lot gate) and employees will provide the sacked items.

The FPES service will be 10:30 a.m. to noon. Participants are asked to pull up to the student drop off driveway to receive their items. #ajusd

The graduating class of Apache Junction High School’s class of 2020 will shine in a way like no other class in the school’s history.
Beginning Friday, April 17 at 8:20 p.m., the lights on the football field will shine for 20 minutes to honor the school’s graduating seniors. The lights will continue to go on every Friday at 8:20 p.m. until May 21, or until further notice.
“We invite the community to help us honor our seniors by turning on their porch lights on each Friday night at 8:20 (2020 military time) and keeping them on for 20 minutes in honor of the class of 2020,” said Dr. Chris Lineberry, principal of AJHS. “#ajusd

post_text: The AJ Elks Lodge have received free vouchers for AJUSD students, staff, parents and members of the community to receive vouchers to pay to receive a food handlers card ($10 value). From there you can do the online training and take a test to receive a food handlers card. This card is needed for jobs that require food handling. Whether you are a student who wants to work in the food industry, a parent who wants to do fundraising at a snack stand (when those options open up again) or a member of the community that wants to help out the local food bank, this card is a must. Contact Heather.Wallace@goaj.org for information on how to proceed. And to our wonderful AJ Elks Lodge - thank you, thank you, thank you from #ajusd.

post_text:
The AJUSD curbside meal service is gearing up again. The school district will continue to provide curbside meal service once a week on Mondays.

The program provides sack meals with FIVE days’ (a change from the USDA) worth of groceries at two locations, Apache Junction High School, 2525 S. Ironwood Dr. and Four Peaks Elementary School, 1785 N. Idaho Road in Apache Junction. Each sack includes frozen items that can be prepared at home. This free service is available for all children 18 years and younger. Children must be in the car to receive the items.

The meal service for the AJHS site is 10 to 11:30 a.m. Participants are asked to pull in at the drive east of the football field on Southern and follow the drive around the field to the cafeteria, just under the Davis Field sign. AJUSD food services staff will provide sacked items for every child who is in the car. The FPES service will be 10:30 a.m. to noon. Participants are asked to pull up to the student drop off driveway to receive their items.

The program will continue until further notice and while supplies last.#ajusd

The demand for the #AJUSD curbside meal service far exceeded our expectations. We apologize for those who did not receive meals.

Please visit the www.ajusd.org site to find other resource options to help you get through this.

This pandemic and all the consequences from it are unprecedented and difficult to predict. That said, we will continue to best serve our community's children. Please work with us.

If you have a specific question, please email me at Sally.Marks@goaj.org and I will try to help you. But please, let's be kind and avoid the non-productive hateful speech that is often seen on Facebook. We can do better. And to those who have been kind, thank you so much. You are an inspiration to others.

post_text:
School may be temporarily closed, but the positive memories live on…

Here we see AJHS First Baseman Remy Wiltz (#20) and his girlfriend Chloe Krueger after a baseball tournament against Avondale. It was the last game the Prospectors played before school closures were mandated due to the coronavirus. Even though the Prospectors lost by one run, it was a great game. Chloe made the long trip out to Avondale to watch Remy play. Chloe is also a student athlete for AJHS who plays soccer and was on the swim team. Thank you to Remy’s proud mom, Ami Gibson, for sharing positive AJUSD memories. Do you have some happy AJUSD memories to share? If so, email Sally.Marks@goaj.org a picture and a little about the memory so it can be shared with others. And it doesn’t have to be the high school. All AJUSD schools are eligible to share #ajusd. Help spread the joy!

post_text:
And the Band Plays On…

Even while #ajusd schools are on Spring Break (and closed next week to prevent the spread of COVID-19) that doesn’t mean there aren’t some positive messages to share about our schools and district. These pictures are from Sara Hermann who is a dedicated “Band Mom”. Here’s what she had to say:

“My twins are seniors this year and so much is going around about the senior class. They were born during the 9/11 tragedy and now they are graduating during the world shut down. Now my boys went from enjoying their spring break to working overtime and becoming some of the most essential employees in the country. They work at Bashas'. They really stepped up to the challenge. I’m so proud of them!”

If you have pictures, memories or some positive messages you’d like to share on the AJUSD Facebook site, please email me at Sally.Marks@goaj.org and I will share your stories. Stories may be edited as needed. And don’t forget to continue to visit the www.ajusd.org site for the latest updates on COVID-19 and school closures.

post_text:
March 16, 2020

Dear Patrons of the Arizona Lecture Series:

It is with saddening hearts to inform you that the remainder of the Arizona Lecture Series season is cancelled due to a statewide school district shutdown in response to the COVID-19 outbreak. We hope you have enjoyed spending your Monday nights and learning about all the fascinating history that makes Arizona so unique. We promise that the series will be back for its 2021 season. For those who have purchased tickets to “Armed with Our Language” and/or “Doc Holliday” we encourage you to hold onto your tickets as they will be credited to next year’s season.

All the Best,
Zach Lundquest
Arizona Lecture Series Coordinator

post_text:
AJHS Wrestlers Stay Strong!
The big news for the Prospectors came with Cody Arbogast becoming the first Apache Junction state champion since 2006! The wrestler weighs in at 195. AJ also had a couple other placers. Ethan Wright was pinned in his 182 finals match with Robert White of Safford, who improved to 55-0 on the year. Preston Lindstrom finished sixth after he was pinned by Ulises Gutierrez of Flagstaff Coconino at 220. Congratulations!

post_text:
Who Loves Soccer?

The fun folks at AJ Parks & Rec are offering youth soccer leagues for boys and girls ages 4-11, divided into three age groups. Youth ages 4-5 will play on Monday and Wednesday evenings from 6-7pm. Youth ages 6-8 & 8-11 will play on Monday & Wednesday evenings (6-7pm/7-8pm) and Saturday mornings (10-11am/11am-12pm). All leagues will be at Prospector Park (3015 N. Idaho Rd.). Registration fees are only $40 for the 4-5 year old league, $45 for the 6-8 year old league and $50 for the 8-11 year old league. There is a $5 per participant discount if registered by January 2nd. We are actively recruiting for volunteer coaches for all three leagues.

post_text: A member from the Arizona Humane Society and a member of the Phoenix Zoo’s zoo keeper staff came into Caerensa Klauss' 5th grade classroom at Desert Vista Elementary School to teach the students about some critters. Holiday Giving

Apache Junction Unified School District wants to extend a BIG thank you to the Tuesday Dinner Club for their generous donation of $450. Instead of buying each other gifts this year for Christmas the group decided to donate the money to help others. The money will be used to buy food and toys for two families in the school district who have fallen on hard times. Thank you for your generous contribution. #ajusd

shared_text:
Cactus Canyon Jr. High is in Washington D.C.
November 23, 2019 at 7:28 PM · Washington D.C. ·

The yearbook had a big day at the National High School Journalism Convention in DC! Dia Granillo won first place for Middle School Story of the Year and Amber Henderson and Emily Sosa got fifth place in the same category. Emily also received an Honorable Mention for Design of the Year and the whole staff got seventh place in Best of Show. It was so much that Mr. Davis has to recruit some California kids to help hold awards for a photo. Congratulations to these amazing students; they earned these awards with hard work and dedication! @ Washington D.C.

post_text:
Halloween Fun at CCJH!

Kids aren’t the only ones who had fun on Halloween. At Cactus Canyon Junior High the 8th grade team of core teachers wore shirts with a Hocus Pocus theme. The shirts were created by Diana Kidde. #ajusd

The ladies’ shirts had more sparkle than the guy’s version (the no-sparkle ban was the only way they would wear a shirt). The ladies’ shirts said, “I smell children.” The guy’s shirts said, “It's all just a bunch of Hocus Pocus.”

CCJH has a very special group of teachers. They work together, have fun and display a true spirit of teamwork and camaraderie. The picture was taken by Jenny Powell right after lunch.

Caption: (left to right) Bryson Maxwell, Daniel Powell, Mallory Stradling, Lydia, Heather Maertens Varney, Angel Wilson, Diana Kidde (shirt maker) and Mike Hopkins. Missing from the picture are Lisa Smith and Regan Roach for pictures.

Sophomore Chess Player Makes the Right Moves
AJHS hosted a state-qualifying tournament Oct. 25-26 with 15 school and 73 players battling for an opportunity to compete at state. Congratulations to Brandon Henderson who earned a medal for his top 15 placement at the end of the tourney. Brandon is a sophomore, so we expect to hear much more from him over the next two years. Congratulations Brandon! #ajusd

post_text: Grease rehearsals are going great. Be sure to mark your calendar for 7 p.m. either Nov. 7 and 8 at the Performing Arts Center at AJ High to see this cool production. One starring role still needs to be cast - the car, Greased Lightning. If you have a 1940s to 1950s car you would like to see on stage, contact smarks@goaj.org and let's see what we can work out. Even a "junker" car could have a starring role!

post_text: Did you buy too much candy for the five trick or treaters that come to your house? Maybe that was only my neighborhood last year, but if you want to donate individually-wrapped candy for Four Peaks Elementary Schools Harvest Festival, please drop off donations at the school before Friday, Oct. 25. The school is located at 1785 N. Idaho Road in AJ. If you don't want to donate candy, other inexpensive treats such as stickers, mini play doh, glow sticks, small flashlights etc. also make great trick or treat gifts. Thanks. #ajusd
